2026-04-16 12:07:06 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module - timing circuit (possibly timer IC or control logic)'] hypothesis_explanation='The system symptoms point to a periodic dropout in voltage to the load module, causing both the load lamp and its indicator to turn off for about half a second every 20 seconds. Diagnostic testing has ruled out faults in the main lamp, indicator lamp, relay, ambient light sensor, protection diode, module interconnections, and the power supply. During the off interval, a very low voltage is provided at the load input, indicating the control relay is actually not conducting load voltage to the load, despite being physically in the closed position.\n\nThe period and regularity of this anomaly point directly to the timing/control function within the control module. Testing shows that the relay is energized, its contacts are closed, and there is continuity, but there is no current through the relay during operation, which is anomalous. Also, the timing potentiometer lacks a functional resistance parameter. These clues suggest a faulty timer circuit or IC, or a related critical failure in the logic block that periodically disables (likely by opening the transit path, even if mechanically closed) the power to the load.\n\nTherefore, the root fault is likely a failure in the timing circuit or timer IC/control logic in the control module intermittently and periodically interrupting load current despite the physical relay closure.'
